Galkovsky made the point, but the number "1984" appears a lot in English dystopian writings. Chesterton's "The Napoleon of Notting Hill" is set in 1984. Orwell's wife wrote a poem dedicated to her private school called "1984" about "a nightmarish world with psychotropic weapons".

1984 is obviously the 100 year anniversary of the Fabian Society, but the original Orwell book had a cover which spaced the titled as "19 84", as in two numbers with a space between them. Galkovsky speculated it's probably one of the Eton College secret society passwords & codes.

That story of Gabe Newell saying strangers started hugging him in public due to the GabeN meme image he had is so sublime to me. He was horrified. He's an autistic old school Linux nerd. He hates being touched. But he had to do it. Had to embrace them. You have a DUTY to others.

It's such a simple story, but it's a microcosm of man's entire relationship with other people. You can't just betray their expectations. Imagine how sad a fan would be if he met Gabe Newell and went in for a hug and he just pushed him away. You MUST open yourself to those people.

Once others have expectations of you, even if you have done nothing to consciously invite them in, you already have a duty. God has given you a talent and GOD will one day come back to see what you have done of it. Even if it's scary and uncomfortable. You have to hug the people.

This little anecdote has the same significance to me as those sayings about the Buddha. Gabe Newell uncomfortably hugging a fan on the street not to disappoint his expectations...

"He, who can at all times sacrifice pleasure to duty, approaches sublimity."
